'''James Harrington Trafford''' (born 10 October 2002) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for {{English football updater|ManchesC}} club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].

==Early life==
Trafford was born in [[Cockermouth]], Cumbria,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/content/a-closer-look-at-james-traffords-background |title=A closer look at James Trafford's background |publisher=Burnley F.C. |date=23 July 2023 |access-date=26 July 2025}}</ref> and grew up in the nearby village of [[Greysouthen]] in a farming family.<ref name = "ManCity"/> He was a [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] fan.<ref name = "ManCity"/> He attended [[Cockermouth School]] and [[St Bede's College, Manchester|St Bede's College]].<ref name = "ManCity"/> He learned to drive on a tractor<ref name="auto">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66121133|title=From farm to final – England's future number one?|work=BBC Sport |date=7 July 2023 }}</ref> and in his early career he would return to help out on the family farm in the off-season.<ref name="auto2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jul/04/james-trafford-england-under-21-european-championship|title=James Trafford is the rising star with designs on being England's No 1|first=Ben|last=Fisher|date=4 July 2023|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Manchester City===
Trafford began his career with Cockermouth and [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]], signing with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in August 2015 at the age of 12.<ref name = "ManCity">{{Cite web|title=James, 12, signs for mega-rich Man City|url=https://www.timesandstar.co.uk/sport/17030219.james-12-signs-for-mega-rich-man-city/|access-date=6 September 2021|website=Times and Star|date=28 August 2015 }}</ref> At Carlisle he began as a [[midfielder]] but volunteered to become a goalkeeper at age nine.<ref name="auto2"/> He was part of the Manchester City Under-18s team that won the 2019–20 [[Professional Development League|Professional U18 Development]] League and the Under-23s team that won the [[2020–21 Professional U23 Development League]].<ref name=mancity>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/james-trafford-joins-manchester-city-63889403 |title=Trafford returns to Manchester City! |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=29 July 2025 |access-date=29 July 2025}}</ref>
 
He moved on loan to [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in July 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57678725|title=Accrington sign Mumbongo and Trafford|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> This loan was later described as "challenging" due to injuries and losing his first-team place.<ref name="auto2"/>

====Bolton Wanderers====
Trafford signed on loan for [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 13 January 2022, until the end of the 2021–22 season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59987947|title=James Trafford: Bolton Wanderers sign Manchester City goalkeeper |website=BBC Sport }}</ref> He kept four [[clean sheet]]s in his first four games, the first time a goalkeeper had done so in Bolton's entire history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/19876206.bolton-wanderers-manchester-city-loanee-james-trafford-reveals-farming-past/|title='I'm just a farm boy at heart' – Wanderers keeper Trafford on his rural roots|website=The Bolton News|date=26 January 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/2022/February/report-wanderers-v-cambridge-utd/|title='REPORT: Wanderers 2 Cambridge Utd 0|website=Bolton Wanderers Official Website}}</ref><ref name="auto"/>

On 15 June 2022, Trafford rejoined Bolton on loan for a further season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/2022/june/trafford-back-for-more/|title=Trafford Back For More|website=Bolton Wanderers Official Website}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61818486 | title=Trafford rejoins Bolton on loan from Man City | website=BBC Sport }}</ref> In July 2022, he signed a new five-year contract with Manchester City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-city-james-trafford-bolton-24508791|title=Man City goalkeeper on League One return over Championship loan|first=John|last=McDougall|date=16 July 2022|website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> By October he was noted for his clean sheets,<ref name=haul>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/bolton-james-trafford-manchester-city-25245526|title=Bolton goalkeeper Trafford's impressive clean sheet haul & League One standings|first=John|last=McDougall|date=12 October 2022|website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> and Trafford broke Bolton's record for consecutive home clean sheets on 4 February, with the 1–0 win over [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] being his eighth in a row.<ref name=record2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/2023/february/trafford-record-is-a-group-effort/|title=Trafford: Record Is A Group Effort|website=www.bwfc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/sport/23302734.james-trafford-helps-bolton-wanderers-break-home-clean-sheet-record/|title=Cumbrian goalkeeper helps club break record|website=News and Star|date=6 February 2023 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/james-trafford-man-city-bolton-26157121|title=Man City goalkeeping pecking order might be set to change|first=Dan|last=Brown|date=4 February 2023|website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> He was able to extend the record to nine,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64549561|title=Bolton Wanderers 5–0 Milton Keynes Dons|website=BBC Sport }}</ref><ref name="auto"/> though was unable to have it reach double figures as on 25 February he conceded against [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] in a 2–1 win, the first time since 2 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64686130|title=Bolton Wanderers 2–1 Port Vale|website=BBC Sport }}</ref> On 2 April, he started in the [[2023 EFL Trophy final]] and kept a clean sheet in 4–0 win against [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]].<ref name="EFLT23"/> Trafford's clean sheet in a 1–0 win against [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewbury Town]] on 22 April was his 25th of the season, which broke the record for the most clean sheets by a Bolton goalkeeper in one season.<ref name=record3>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/23474574.bolton-wanderers-1-0-shrewsbury-town---marc-iless-big-match-verdict/|title=Bolton Wanderers 1–0 Shrewsbury Town – Marc Iles's big match verdict|first=Iles|last=Marc|date=23 April 2023|website=The Bolton News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/23491094.liverpool-teen-conor-bradley-wins-hat-trick-bolton-wanderers-awards/|title=Liverpool teen Conor Bradley wins hat-trick of Bolton Wanderers awards|first=Iles|last=Marc|date=30 April 2023|website=The Bolton News}}</ref> He finished the season with a total of 26 clean sheets.<ref name="auto"/> He helped Bolton qualify for the [[2023 English Football League play-offs#League One|play-offs]], though they were defeated by [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65567452|title=Barnsley edge past Bolton to reach play-off final|work=BBC Sport |date=18 May 2023 }}</ref> He was voted as Bolton's Young Player of the Year for the [[2022–23 Bolton Wanderers F.C. season|2022–23]] season, together with [[Conor Bradley]].<ref name="BWPOTY">{{cite news |date=29 April 2023 |title=Bradley Is Season Star |website=Bolton Wanderers |url=https://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/2023/april/bradley-is-season-star/ |access-date=29 April 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Iles |first=Marc |date=30 April 2023 |title='We're not finished yet!' Prize guy Conor wants more glory in the play-offs |url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/23491094.liverpool-teen-conor-bradley-wins-hat-trick-bolton-wanderers-awards/ |access-date=5 May 2023 |website=The Bolton News}}</ref> His performances during the season saw him named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] for League One.<ref name=PFA>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66650723 |title=Erling Haaland: Manchester City forward wins PFA men's Player of the Year award |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 August 2023 |access-date=29 August 2023}}</ref> He said his time at Bolton turned him from a "long, skinny boy" into a "long, skinny man".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/23521485.manchester-city-keeper-james-traffords-thank-you-bolton-wanderers/|title=James Trafford's thank-you message to Wanderers after play-off heroics|date=15 May 2023|website=The Bolton News}}</ref>

Since leaving Bolton, Trafford has consistently expressed his love for the club, going as far as to say "I am a Bolton fan, I love Bolton. Everyone in the club, I loved them."<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 June 2025 |title='I couldn't love Bolton any more!' - James Trafford looks back at loan days |url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/25220155.england-keeper-james-trafford-love-bolton-wanderers/ |access-date=6 April 2026 |website=The Bolton News |language=en}}</ref>

===Burnley===
On 3 July 2023, it was announced that a £15 million transfer fee had been agreed between Manchester City and [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] for Trafford.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66093009|title=Burnley agree £15m deal for Man City's Trafford|work=BBC Sport |date=3 July 2023 }}</ref> With add-ons, the deal could reach a total of £19 million — which if met would break Burnley's transfer record.<ref name="auto"/> On 20 July 2023, Trafford's move to Burnley was officially completed.<ref>{{cite web |title=CLARETS CAPTURE TRAFFORD |url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/content/clarets-capture-trafford |publisher=Burnley Football Club |access-date=20 July 2023 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66262753|title=Burnley sign Man City's Trafford in £19m deal|work=BBC Sport |date=20 July 2023 }}</ref> Due to their sell-on clause, Carlisle United got 15% of the fee for around £2.25m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/sport/23660796.reports-claim-carlisle-united-cash-james-trafford-move/|title=Report makes claim about Carlisle United cash from keeper transfer|date=17 July 2023|website=News and Star}}</ref> He became the third most expensive British goalkeeper in history.<ref name="auto1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12919060/james-trafford-man-city-youth-product-and-u21-penalty-hero-is-a-future-england-no-1-who-can-shine-at-burnley|title=James Trafford: Man City youth product and U21 penalty hero is a future England No 1 who can shine at Burnley|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

He made his Burnley and Premier League debut on 11 August 2023, in a 3–0 home defeat to his former club, Manchester City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/sport/23718526.james-trafford-makes-premier-league-debut-man-city/|title=Cumbrian keeper makes Premier League debut against Haaland and City|date=12 August 2023|website=News and Star}}</ref> He earned high praise after a Man of the Match performance in a 1–1 draw against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 9 December, in which he made 10 saves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13024886/brighton-1-1-burnley-simon-adingras-second-half-header-denies-relegation-threatened-visitors-shock-win|title=Brighton 1–1 Burnley: James Trafford's late heroics earn relegation-threatened visitors crucial point|website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.burnleyexpress.net/sport/football/vincent-kompanys-immediate-reaction-to-burnleys-draw-at-brighton-james-traffords-solo-display-4440184|title=Vincent Kompany's immediate reaction to Burnley's draw at Brighton & James Trafford's solo display|date=9 December 2023 }}</ref>

In January 2025, he saved two penalties in a league match against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/burnley-sunderland-championship-score-result-table-tsn6pwkpq|title=James Trafford saves two penalties to rescue Burnley against Sunderland|first=Ian|last=Whittell|date=17 January 2025|website=www.thetimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/24866824.james-trafford-stars-two-penalty-saves-sunderland/|title=Cumbrian keeper stars with TWO penalty saves in one game|date=18 January 2025|website=News and Star}}</ref> being praised by manager [[Scott Parker]] as a "special" player.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/jan/17/burnley-sunderland-championship-match-report|title=Burnley's Parker hails 'special' Trafford after penalty saves deny Sunderland|first=Will|last=Unwin|work=The Guardian |date=17 January 2025}}</ref> Having not conceded a goal across any of their six matches in the month, he was named [[EFL Championship Player of the Month]].<ref name="Jan25 POTM">{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2025/february/07/sky-bet-championship-manager---player-of-the-month-january-winners/|title=Sky Bet Championship Manager & Player of the Month January winners|website=www.efl.com|date=7 February 2025|accessdate=7 February 2025}}</ref> By February 2025, Trafford had gone 1,000 minutes without conceding a goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cq8kle2x81do|title=Burnley: The stats behind the Clarets' 1,000 minutes without conceding|date=15 February 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In March 2025, this streak came to an end in Burnley's [[EFL Championship]] match against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], with [[Yousef Salech]] scoring in the 42nd minute.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 March 2025 |title=JJ Watt can stay in retirement after James Trafford's clean sheet streak ends |url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/jj-watt-stay-retirement-james-210340514.html?guccounter=1 |access-date=4 March 2025 |website=Yahoo Sports }}</ref> During this run, Trafford kept 12 clean sheets in a row, breaking the record for the most consecutive clean sheets in Championship history (the prior record was 10).<ref name=champsrecord>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6134300/2025/03/04/burnley-clean-sheet-record/|title=Burnley concede after record 12 league clean sheets in a row to keep JJ Watt in NFL retirement|first1=Alex|last1=Brodie|first2=Colin|last2=Millar|work=The New York Times |date=4 March 2025|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> After 33 games, Trafford and Burnley had conceded only nine goals, the fewest in the history of English Football at that point of the season.<ref name=champsrecord2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11708/13311885/james-trafford-interview-burnley-goalkeeper-on-clean-sheet-record-jj-watt-wager-and-sunderland-penalty-saves|title=James Trafford interview: Burnley goalkeeper on clean-sheet record, JJ Watt wager and Sunderland penalty saves|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Trafford finished the season with 29 clean sheets,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/james-traffords-verdict-remarkable-season-102347157.html|title=James Trafford's verdict on remarkable season and transfer 'noise'|date=29 April 2025|website=Yahoo Sports}}</ref> which equalled the record for a goalkeeper in a single season in English football.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cx2vkk6rn3vt|title=Queens Park Rangers v Burnley: Championship stats & head-to-head|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> During the 2024–25 season, Burnley conceded only 16 goals in 46 games, the fewest in the history of the Football League, beating the previous record of 20,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cdjlv2e02dyo|title=Championship: Leeds United and Burnley's historic title race|date=3 May 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref name=champsrecord2/> although this was one more than [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s 15 conceded in 38 games in the [[2004–05 Chelsea F.C. season|2004–05]] Premier League.<ref name=champsrecord2/>

===Return to Manchester City===
On 29 July 2025, Manchester City announced the return of Trafford on a five-year deal, after activating their buy-back clause and matching [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]'s £31 million bid.<ref name=mancity/><ref name=recordfee>{{cite news |last=Stafford |first=Katie |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cgk3k0654x6o |title=Keeper Trafford returns 'home' to Man City for £27m |website=BBC Sport |date=29 July 2025 |access-date=29 July 2025}}</ref><ref name=recordfee2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/13402939/james-trafford-transfer-news-man-city-complete-deal-to-re-sign-goalkeeper-from-burnley|title=James Trafford transfer news: Man City complete deal to re-sign goalkeeper from Burnley &#124; Football News &#124; Sky Sports |work=Sky Sports }}</ref> Trafford's official fee was £31 million (being the record paid for a British goalkeeper), although City received £4 million back due to their sell-on clause, and so only paid £27 million.<ref name=recordfee/><ref name=recordfee2/> On 16 August, he made his debut for City in their first Premier League game of the season, keeping a clean sheet in a 4–0 away win against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/wolves-manchester-city-202526-match-report-63890951 |title=Super City make blistering Premier League start at Wolves |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=16 August 2025 |access-date=17 August 2025}}</ref> In his home debut for City on 23 August, he made an error that led to Tottenham Hotspur's second goal in a 2–0 defeat. After the game, Guardiola said he still backed Trafford.<ref>{{Cite news |date=29 August 2025 |title=Man City's Guardiola backs keeper Trafford after Spurs error |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/man-citys-guardiola-backs-keeper-trafford-after-spurs-error-2025-08-29/ |access-date=7 September 2025 |work=Reuters }}</ref> Trafford was presented with the August [[Premier League Save of the Month|Save of the Month]] award for saving a close-range shot by [[Jan Paul van Hecke]] as City lost 2–1 to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 31 August.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rajan |first=Adwaidh |date=31 August 2025 |title=Brajan Gruda came off the bench to score an 89th-minute goal to give Brighton their first win of the Premier League season, while condemning Manchester City to back-to-back defeats. |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c80dn91vz3kt |access-date=14 September 2025 |work=[[BBC News]] |department=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=12 September 2025 |title=Trafford wins Coca-Cola Save of the Month award |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4407234/trafford-wins-coca-cola-save-of-the-month-award |access-date=14 September 2025 |website=[[Premier League]]}}</ref>

After playing in the club's first few matches, he was dropped in favour of transfer deadline day signing [[Gianluigi Donnarumma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c75q1g6dyk2o|title=James Trafford: Will Man City goalkeeper be questioning return?|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|date=24 September 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Thereafter Trafford appeared only in Cup games,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cq8dw32q2g2o|title=Man City 2–0 Brentford: Should James Trafford 'stick it out' at the club?|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|date=17 December 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> with former Man City goalkeeper [[Nicky Weaver]] saying he "felt sorry" for Trafford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c989kz4ngeyo|title=Manchester City news: Nicky Weaver on James Trafford|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|date=18 December 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 22 March 2026, Trafford started in the [[2026 EFL Cup final|EFL Cup final]], securing a 2–0 victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and becoming the second youngest goalkeeper to achieve this feat, surpassed only by [[Chris Woods]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/man-city-stopper-marks-historic-efl-cup-final-feat-in-incredible-style-42599393 |title=Man City stopper marks historic EFL Cup final feat in incredible style |publisher=OneFootball |date=22 March 2026 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Paul |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/james-trafford-carabao-cup-2026-success-63909803 |title=Trafford on Carabao Cup win: It's an amazing, amazing feeling |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=22 March 2026 }}</ref> On 16 May he started the [[2026 FA Cup final|FA Cup final]], with Man City beating [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 1–0 — meaning Trafford and City won both domestic cups that season.<ref name=FA26>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/clypx2em7drt#Line-ups |title=Chelsea 0–1 Manchester City |website=BBC Sport |date=16 May 2026 |access-date=16 May 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Trafford played his first international match of his career for [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]] on 24 March 2018 against [[Croatia national under-17 football team|Croatia U17]] in which he saved a penalty and kept a [[clean sheet]] in a 0–0 draw despite England being down to ten men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2019/mar/24/england-u17s-croatia-report-240319|title=Drama in Denmark as ten-men England held to a draw by Croatia in Euro qualifying|first=The Football|last=Association|website=www.thefa.com}}</ref> He made a further six appearances for the U17 including one appearance at the [[2019 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]], then played twice for [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]], and once for [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe562368/james-trafford/international-matches/|title=James Trafford » Internationals|website=worldfootball.net |date=29 July 2025 }}</ref>

On 6 September 2021, Trafford made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England U20s]] during a 6–1 victory over [[Romania national under-20 football team|Romania U20s]] at [[St George's Park National Football Centre|St. George's Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Six at SGP for MU20s|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2021/Sep/06/20210609-england-mu20s-romania-match-report|access-date=6 September 2021|website=EnglandFootball.com|publisher=[[The Football Association]]}}</ref>

On 25 May 2022, Trafford received his first call up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] squad ahead of the final round of [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] matches.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=25 May 2022|title=Lee Carsley has made his pick for Young Lions' four games in June as they target MU21 EURO qualification|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/May/25/england-mu21s-squad-named-for-june-euro-qualifiers-czech-republic-albania-kosovo-slovenia-20222505|access-date=25 May 2022|website=EnglandFootball.com|publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> Trafford made his debut in the 5–0 win away to [[Kosovo national under-21 football team|Kosovo]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=10 June 2022|title=Match report: Kosovo 0–5 England MU21s|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Jun/10/england-mu21s-kosovo-match-u21-euro-qualifier-report-20221006|access-date=12 June 2022|website=EnglandFootball.com|publisher=The Football Association}}</ref>

On 14 June 2023, Trafford was included in the England squad for the [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=14 June 2023|title=England MU21s squad named for EURO Finals|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Jun/14/england-mens-under-21s-squad-named-for-uefa-u21-euro-finals-20231406|access-date=26 June 2023|website=EnglandFootball.com|publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> He did not concede a goal during the tournament in six matches,<ref name="auto"/> the first time a goalkeeper had done this in the tournament's history,<ref name=u21final2>{{cite web |title=England U21 1–0 Spain U21: England win Under-21 Euros for first time in 39 years |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66127349 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=8 July 2023 |date=8 July 2023|first=Alex|last=Howell}}</ref> and saved a stoppage-time penalty and its rebound in the final against Spain as England won the game 1–0.<ref name=u21final>{{Cite web |last=Athletic |first=The |date=8 July 2023 |title=England vs Spain live updates |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/england-spain-u21-euro-2023-live-score-updates-result-final/jJM8XeO5HRos/ |access-date=8 July 2023 |website=The Athletic }}</ref> His mentality was praised by England under-21 manager [[Lee Carsley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66145646|title=Trafford has 'top mentality' to succeed – Carsley|work=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2023 }}</ref> It was later reported that Trafford had told friends that he would save a penalty that game.<ref name="auto1"/>

Following an injury to [[Sam Johnstone]] in March 2024, Trafford received his first call up to the [[England national football team|senior]] squad for a friendly against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2024/Mar/19/england-mens-squad-updates-march-international-window-2024 |title=England squad update: Rico Lewis and James Trafford join seniors |first=Andy |last=Walker |website=EnglandFootball.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=24 March 2024 |access-date=24 March 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68651573|title=England's Walker & Maguire ruled out of Belgium game|work=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2024 }}</ref> He was selected to England's provisional 33-member squad for [[Euro 2024]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c3gglr8mpzdo|title=England Euro 2024 squad: Marcus Rashford and Jordan Henderson left out of Gareth Southgate's provisional squad|date=21 May 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> but was dropped from the final 26-man squad on 6 June.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 |access-date=6 June 2024}}</ref>

In October 2025, Manchester City manager [[Pep Guardiola]] said that Trafford would become an England goalkeeper in due course.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cly13z02v2lo|title=James Trafford: Man City keeper will be England number one 'sooner or later'|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|date=28 October 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 27 March 2026 Trafford made his full England international debut in a friendly against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]]. He conceded a stoppage time penalty, with the match ending in a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/bulletin/sport/garner-trafford-england-uruguay-tuchel-b2947351.html |title=England duo handed debuts by Thomas Tuchel in pre-World Cup friendly |website=Independent |date=27 March 2026 |access-date=27 March 2026}}</ref>

==Style of play==
He spent his early career as an outfield player.<ref name = "ManCity"/> At Carlisle he began as a [[midfielder]], but volunteered to become a goalkeeper at age nine.<ref name="auto2"/> He has been praised for his reflexes and distribution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4407763/2023/04/15/james-trafford-man-city-bolton/|title=Rapid reflexes and pin-point distribution can take Bolton's City loanee Trafford to the top|first=Nancy|last=Froston|website=The Athletic |date=15 April 2023 }}</ref> He is noted for his ability to keep [[clean sheet]]s, breaking multiple records with [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]],<ref name=haul/><ref name="auto"/><ref name=record2/><ref name=record3/> [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]],<ref name=champsrecord/><ref name=champsrecord2/> and winning the [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] without conceding a goal.<ref name="auto"/><ref name=u21final/><ref name=u21final2/>

==Personal life==
In 2025, two years after leaving [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], Trafford revealed he loved his time at the club so much that it had caused him to become a Bolton fan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/25220155.england-keeper-james-trafford-love-bolton-wanderers/|title='I couldn't love Bolton any more!' – James Trafford looks back at loan days|date=7 June 2025|website=The Bolton News}}</ref>

